The ﬁrst steps in the assembly of the polyketide chain resemble that of fatty acid biosynthesis.1 Small carbon units are fused to build up the linear polyketide chain.2 In the biosynthesis of aromatic Abbreviations used: NAME, nogalonic acid methyl ester; PEG, polyethylene glycol; rmsd, root-mean-square deviation; ORF, open-reading frame; MAD, multiple wavelength anomalous diffraction. 0022-2836/$ - see front matter q 2006 Elsevier Ltd. SnoaL2 and AclR are homologous enzymes in the biosynthesis of the aromatic polyketides nogalamycin in Streptomyces nogalater and cinerubin in Streptomyces galilaeus, respectively. Evidence obtained from gene transfer experiments suggested that SnoaL2 catalyzes the hydroxylation of the C-1 carbon atom of the polyketide chain. Here we show that AclR is also involved in the production of 1-hydroxylated anthracyclines in vivo. The three-dimensional structure of SnoaL2 has been determined by multi- wavelength anomalous diffraction to 2.5 A˚ resolution, and that of AclR to 1.8 A˚ resolution using molecular replacement. Both enzymes are dimers in solution and in the crystal. The fold of the enzyme subunits consists of an aCb barrel. The dimer interface is formed by packing of the b-sheets from the two subunits against each other. In the interior of the aCb barrel a hydrophobic cavity is formed that most likely binds the substrate and harbors the active site. The subunit fold and the architecture of the active site in SnoaL2 and AclR are similar to that of the polyketide cyclases SnoaL and AknH; however, they show completely different quaternary structures. A comparison of the active site pockets of the putative hydroxylases AclR and SnoaL2 with those of bona ﬁde polyketide cyclases reveals distinct differences in amino acids lining the cavity that might be responsible for the switch in chemistry. The moderate degree of sequence similarity and the preservation of the three-dimensional fold of the polypeptide chain suggest that these enzymes are evolutionary related. Members of this enzyme family appear to have evolved from a common protein scaffold by divergent evolution to catalyze reactions chemically as diverse as aldol condensation and hydroxylation. Keywords: anthracycline; enzyme mechanism; evolution; protein crystallography; protein structure

One large class of aromatic polyketides are the anthracyclines, which contain a 7,8,9,10 tetrahydro-5,12 naphtacenedione core. The structural diversity of anthracyclines is generated by variations in the modiﬁcation pattern of the aglycone scaffold. The reactions leading to the differences in substitution proﬁle are catalyzed by tailoring enzymes and include methylation, hydroxylation, reduction and glycosylation.1,4,5 Glycosylation of the aglycone core is essential for biological activity and increases water solubility.6 q 2006 Elsevier Ltd. Anthracyclines are of particular medical import- ance, because several clinically employed anti- tumor drugs are recruited from this class of secondary metabolites.1,7,8

Nogalamycin (Figure 1(a)), an antibiotic pro- duced by Streptomyces nogalater, differs from most other anthracyclines in the stereochemistry at C-9 (C-9S rather than C-9R), a methyl instead of an ethyl substituent at C-9, and additional glycosylation at C-1 with a highly unusual C–C bond to the C-2 carbon atom.9 The entire gene cluster for nogala- mycin biosynthesis has been cloned, and the function of most of the individual proteins encoded by these genes has been determined by a combi- nation of genetic and biochemical approaches.10 The cluster consists of 35 open reading frames, of which 17 are related to carbohydrate biosynthesis and glycosyl transfer, 11 are involved in the production of the aglycone core, one in regulation and one in resistance. The functions of the remaining ﬁve open-reading frames (ORFs) are still unknown. A distinguishing feature in nogala- mycin biosynthesis is the hydroxylation at the C-1 position, because it provides the point of attach- ment of the carbohydrate chain unique for this anthracycline. The biosynthetic route to C-1/C-2 modiﬁcations is of interest because these positions are not modiﬁed in anthracyclines in clinical use today and hybrid-anthracyclines generated by transfer of the genes for the complete C-1/C-2 glycosylation pathway could have useful novel toxicological proﬁles. Transfer of the snoaL2 gene (in sequence data- bases snoL) from the nogalamycin biosynthetic cluster into the aklavinone producing Streptomyces galilaeus mutants H063 and H039 resulted in the production of 1-hydroxyaklavinone (Figure 1(b)), suggesting that SnoaL2 is the C-1 hydroxylase responsible for the ﬁrst step in the C-1/C-2 glycosylation modiﬁcation of nogalamycin.10 This ﬁnding further suggested that hydroxylation occurs

at the level of the aglycone, because the S. galileus mutant H063 is deﬁcient in aklavinone glycosyla- tion. Modiﬁcations at the C-1 position of the aglycone backbone are also found in the secondary metabolites of other Streptomyces strains.1,11,12 The gene cluster described by Chung et al.13 (Genbank accession code AB008466) is derived from a strain that originally produced 1-hydroxylated cinerubins in addition to aclacinomycin (MA 144-M1ZATCC 31133).14 However, the authors sequenced the cluster from a mutant strain, which only produces aklavinone, and which is deﬁcient in 1-hydroxy- lation. This gene cluster contains a gene homolo- gous to snoaL2 (59% identity on amino acid level), denoted aclR. Here, we demonstrate that aclR also encodes an enzyme that can catalyze C-1 hydroxy- lation in vivo. The mutant strain deﬁcient in hydroxylation may contain an inactivating struc- tural or regulatory mutation.

SnoaL2 and AclR are small proteins of about 140 amino acid residues that show no sequence similarities to ﬂavin or metal-dependent hydro- xylases, and are thus putative cofactorless hydro- xylases.15 Instead, they exhibit weak sequence similarities to members of a family of polyketide cyclases, exempliﬁed by SnoaL,16,17 AknH18,19 and DnrD.20 The mechanisms and reaction pathway of the C-1/ C-2 modiﬁcations of the aglycone moiety are not fully understood, and as a ﬁrst step towards the elucidation of the underlying enzymatic mechan- isms, we have determined the 3D structures of AclR and SnoaL2 by protein crystallography. The struc- ture analysis shows that the fold of the two enzymes is similar to that of the polyketide cyclases SnoaL and AknH. The packing of the subunits in dimeric AclR and SnoaL2 is, however, very different from that of the tetrameric cyclases. SnoaL/SnoaL2 and AknH/AclR are striking examples of how chemical diversity can evolve within an evolutionary related enzyme family and one metabolic pathway. In the Streptomyces expression plasmid pEHA the AclR ORF is expressed from a tandem promoter (ermE and rdmE promoters) with an N-terminal hexahistidine afﬁnity tag. Transfer of this construct into a S. galilaeus mutant (H039), which produces aklavinone and neutral glycosides,21 led to the production of a novel orange product (Figure 1(c)), which after total hydrolysis yielded an aglycone indistinguishable from authentic 1-hydroxyakla- vinone by HPLC and UV-spectrophotometry. Trans- formants of wild-type S. galilaeus, when plated from regeneration plates onto ISP4 agar (inorganic salts– starch agar, Difco; which induces anthracycline production) produced poorly growing orange colonies. The production of the orange product, however, proved unstable in liquid culture. Trans- formants of H036 (this strain is blocked at the aklaviketone reductase step, i.e. one step before formation of aklavinone22) failed to grow on ISP4 agar. This indicates that anthracycline aminoglyco- sides and some of the intermediates, when 1-hydroxylated, are toxic to the hosts. Quality of electron density map and model

The structure of SnoaL2 was determined to 2.5 A˚ resolution using multiple wavelength anomalous diffraction (MAD) with seleno-methionine substi- tuted protein (see Materials and Methods). In the electron density map, the complete polypeptide backbone and nearly all amino acid side-chains including the C-terminal linker are visible for subunit A (SnoaL2 residues Ser2–Leu139, and Lys140–Ala147 from the peptide linking SnoaL2 with the C-terminal hexahistidine tag). In chain B the C-terminal part of the protein is less well deﬁned and no electron density is visible after residue Val134. There is no electron density for bound aklavinone, although it had been included in the crystallization solution. The ﬁnal model of SnoaL2 consists of 2262 non-hydrogen protein atoms and 31 water molecules. The quality is as expected for this resolution with no amino acid residues in the disallowed region of the Ramachan- dran plot, a root-mean-square deviation (rmsd) value for bond lengths of 0.015 A˚ and an rmsd for bond angles of 1.458 (Table 1). The subunit folds into one domain that consists of an aCb barrel formed by the central b-sheet and helices H1 to H5 (Figures 2 and 3). The core of the subunit is a curved six-stranded mixed b-sheet (S1–S6) that forms one side of the barrel-like structure. The other side of the barrel is made up Table 1. by three a-helices (H1–H3). Helix H4 extends b-strand S6 and is part of the aCb barrel structure. The C-terminal helix H5 includes residues Asp137– Leu139 from SnoaL2, but is formed mainly from residues of the linker peptide, which are not part of the structure of the native enzyme. This helix folds back over the barrel-like structure and, together with the loop (residues 89–95) that connects b-strands S4 and S5, it closes off a cavity that is formed in the interior of the subunit. the two subunits in the asymmetric unit differ another (Figure 3(b) and (c)). A superposition of the two subunits results in 120 equivalent Ca atoms with an rmsd value of 0.94 A˚ . The differences are localized to a few regions. The largest difference between the structures of the two subunits involves b-strand S6 that is part of the central b-sheet in chain A. In chain B, the C-terminal half of this strand (residues 121– 127) is not part of the b-sheet anymore and instead folds into an extended chain, followed by a one-turn 310-helix at the end. The remaining part of the polypeptide chain is disordered in the crystals. Compared to chain A this stretch of amino acid residues (121–131) in subunit B not only adopts a very different structure, but has also moved closer to the cavity of the barrel. An additional difference between chains A and B is found in the loop region comprising amino acid residues 86–97, which in subunit B is located closer to the entrance of the central cavity. Altogether, these structural differ- ences between the two chains have as a conse- quence that the volume of the central cavity in subunit B is much smaller compared to the volume in chain A (400 A˚ 3 versus 1127 A˚ 3). There are no obvious crystal contacts that may be responsible for these structural differences in the two subunits. In the crystal, SnoaL2 is present as a dimer in the asymmetric unit (Figure 3). Quality of electron density map and model

Crystals of AclR from S. galilaeus diffract to 1.8 A˚ resolution and the structure was solved by molecu- lar replacement using the SnoaL2 structure as the search model. The asymmetric unit of the crystal contains four AclR subunits (labeled A–D), which form two dimers (see below). In the electron density map, the complete enzyme polypeptide chain with the exception of the N-terminal methionine (resi- dues 2–145), including the linker and the C-terminal hexa-histidine tag (residues 146–158) are visible for chain A. In chains B and D the C-terminal part of the protein is less well deﬁned and no electron density is visible after amino acid 134. In chain C all residues up to Leu151 can be traced in the electron density map. The enzyme had been crystallized in the presence of the putative substrate nogalonic acid methyl ester (NAME), but no electron density corresponding to this ligand was found in the electron density maps. In the active site cavity, electron density was observed that could be ﬁtted best with a glycerol molecule from the cryo- protectant and a low molecular mass PEG molecule from the crystallization solution. One additional glycerol molecule was found close to the N terminus of subunit B, and an additional PEG molecule was modelled on the surface of subunit A, in the vicinity of the C-terminal helix H5. The ﬁnal model consists of 4748 non-hydrogen protein atoms, 548 water molecules, ﬁve glycerol and ﬁve PEG molecules. The model is of expected quality for this resolution with no amino acid residues in the disallowed region of the Ramachandran plot, an rmsd value for bond lengths of 0.007 A˚ and an rmsd for bond angles of 1.108 (Table 1).

The overall fold of AclR resembles that of SnoaL2 as expected for two proteins with this degree of sequence identity (Figures 2 and 4). Superposition of the subunits of SnoaL2 and AclR (A chains) results in an rmsd value of 1.28 A˚ , based on 124 equivalent Ca atoms. The asymmetric unit of the crystal contains four subunits that form two dimers. The two subunits of each dimer are related by local 2-fold axes. An additional local 2-fold symmetry axis relates the two dimers, but there are clear deviations from this symmetry between the C termini (residues 138–158) of chain A and its symmetry mate, chain D, from the second dimer. The size of the interface between the two dimers (570 A˚ 2) is typical of a crystal contact, indicating that the molecule is a homo-dimer. The crystallographically determined quaternary struc- ture is consistent with gel ﬁltration experiments that suggested a dimer of AclR in solution (data not shown). The dimers are formed by identical interactions between chain A and B and chain C and D, respectively. Overall, the orientation and the packing between the subunits in the AclR dimer are identical to that seen in SnoaL2 (Figure 4). In total 19 hydrogen bonds and two salt bridges are formed at each dimer interface. Dimer formation buries a surface of approximately 1300 A˚ 2 (16% of the monomer surface), which is similar to the size of the dimerization interface found in SnoaL2. Comparison with related structures

The structures of Snoal2 and AclR contain the aC b barrel fold ﬁrst observed in scytalone dehydra- tase.23 This enzyme is, however, not related in sequence or in mechanism to SnoaL2 and AclR. The closest homologues are the polyketide cyclases SnoaL17 and AknH.19 SnoaL is a polyketide cyclase in the biosynthesis of nogalamycin in S. nogalater that catalyzes the closure of the fourth ring, from NAME to nogalaviketone. A structural superposi- tion of SnoaL with SnoaL2 (chain A) gave an rmsd value of 2.35 A˚ based on 117 equivalent Ca atoms, and similar values (117 equivalent Ca atoms, rmsd 2.08 A˚ ) were obtained from a superposition of SnoaL with AclR. The stretch of the polypeptide chain with the largest structural difference com- prises residues 15–53 (SnoaL numbering) and the last ten C-terminal residues (Figure 5). Because of these structural similarities, we tested the abilities of SnoaL2 and AclR to catalyze the cyclization of NAME, the reaction catalyzed by SnoaL and AknH. No cyclase activity was observed for AclR; SnoaL2 demonstrated a minuscule activity with apparent speciﬁc activity 1/600 of that of the actual cyclase AknH (Figure 6).

While the structures of the subunits of AclR and SnoaL2 thus are rather similar to that of the polyketide cyclases SnoaL and AknH, there are considerable differences in their quaternary struc- tures. SnoaL2 and AclR are dimers, whereas SnoaL and AknH are tetramers. The cyclase tetramers can be described as dimers of dimers.17,19 However, the packing of the subunits in the dimers of SnoaL2 and AclR is very different from that in the dimers of SnoaL and AknH (Figure 7). It is, however, similar to that found in limonene-1,2-epoxide hydrolase24 (Figure 7) and other members of this fold super- family, the nuclear transport factor-2 (NTF2) from rat25 and the hypothetical protein egc068 from a soil-derived mobile gene cassette,26 although there is no signiﬁcant overall sequence similarity (!20% identity). For instance, superposition of the SnoaL2 dimer with limonene 1,2-epoxide hydrolase gives an rmsd value of 2.48 A˚ , based on 226 equivalent Ca atoms. The search for homologous enzymes in sequence databases resulted in one additional close homol- ogue (i.e. O50% sequence identity), ChaU with 57% sequence identity. ChaU is part of the gene cluster coding for the biosynthetic enzymes for the anti- tumor agent chartreusin in Streptomyces chartreusis.27 The physiological function of this gene is, however, not yet established. The close sequence relationship with SnoaL2 and AclR suggests that this enzyme may have a similar function in hydroxylation of the polyketide scaffold. In the crystal structure we observe dual conformations for some of these side-chains (Leu103, Leu107, Met123), reﬂecting conformational ﬂexibility in the absence of bound substrate.

The active site cavity also contains several polar residues, but their distribution and pattern of conservation differs between the bona ﬁde cyclases and the putative hydroxylases, reﬂecting the functional differences between these enzymes. Residues Cys10, His35, and Glu105 are conserved in AclR, SnoaL2 and ChaU (Figure 2), and His117 and Asp119 are invariant in the whole enzyme family, including the polyketide cyclases. Asp119 has been shown to be essential for the catalytic mechanism of the cyclases and has been proposed to participate in proton transfer steps in the aldol condensation reaction.17 On the other hand, residue Gln105 (SnoaL numbering, corresponding position 103 in AclR) is conserved only in the cyclase sequences. In the polyketide cyclases the side- chain of this residue forms the only direct hydrogen bond to the bound ligand, to the carbonyl oxygen atom of the carboxyethyl group of the bound substrate/product.17,19 In the putative hydroxy- lases, this residue is replaced by leucine and tyrosine, respectively, which may interfere with binding of the carboxymethyl group of NAME. Thus, there are subtle differences in the active site topology between the cyclases and the putative hydroxylases that could explain the lack of cyclase activity seen in AclR and SnoaL2.

Polar residues located in the active site pockets that differ between the cyclases on the one hand and the putative hydroxylases on the other hand are Cys10, His35 and Glu105. Therefore, these residues could be involved in the hydroxylation reaction. Glu105 replaces the conserved His107 in the cyclases and is in close vicinity to the invariant residue His117, a residue that shows double conformation in the AclR subunits. In one of the conformations in AclR, and in SnoaL2, the side- chain of His117 is within hydrogen bonding distance to the carboxyl group of Glu105. This interaction could increase the ability of Glu105 to facilitate proton transfer. The unavailability of an enzyme–substrate or enzyme–product complex does, however, not allow more deﬁnite conclusions about residues involved in this highly unusual catalytic mechanism. Although SnoaL210 and AclR (this paper) have been shown to cause the production of 1-hydro- xyaklavinone in vivo, we did not observe hydroxy- lation of stable potential substrates available to us either through bioconversion, cell-free lysates of a culture producing 1-hydroxyaklavinone, or pure SnoaL2 or AclR protein. Furthermore, in spite of extensive efforts to co-crystallize or soak the hydroxylases with NAME (and similar 3-4-ring system compounds), no electron density corre- sponding to such ligands could be observed. These observations suggest that the enzyme acts at an earlier stage in the biosynthetic pathway of the aglycone skeleton. The early intermediates in aromatic polyketide biosynthesis are unstable molecules, probably acyl carrier protein-bound thioesters,28 and are thus not easily accessible for in vitro enzyme assays. In this context it is of interest

to note that in all active sites of AclR a PEG and glycerol molecule were observed in the putative active site pocket (Figure 8). Polyethylene glycol can be considered a simple chemical mimic of a linear polyketide chain, and the binding of PEG may suggest that the active sites of AclR (and possibly also SnoaL2) bind their polyketide substrates in a linear form, consistent with the notion that these enzymes act in the early steps of the biosynthesis of the polyketide scaffold. The precise location of the AclR/SnoaL2 catalyzed hydroxylation reaction in the biosynthetic pathway and the identiﬁcation of the substrate will require extensive in vivo com- plementation studies. The putative polyketide hydroxylases SnoaL2 and AclR from the anthracycline biosynthetic path- ways in Streptomyces are evolutionary related to a class of polyketide cyclases within the same path- way.17 This enzyme family is an illustrative example of how chemical diversity in metabolic pathways can evolve based on a given protein scaffold. Similar dual activities based on one particular fold have been found in other pathways of secondary metabolism. The polyketide cyclase TcmI29 and the cofactorless monooxygenase ActVA-Orf630 are enzymes in the biosynthesis of the aromatic polyketide antibiotics tetracenomycin and actinor- hodin, respectively. Both enzymes show the same fold, but catalyze completely different chemistry, ring closure by aldol condensation and oxygenation of the aromatic polyketide scaffold. It should be noted, however, that TcmI and ActVA-Orf6 are related neither in amino acid sequence nor in fold to the enzyme family exempliﬁed by SnoaL2 and SnoaL. The combination of cyclase and cofactorless monooxygenase/hydroxylase activity within one fold family has thus arisen independently at least twice during the evolution of the pathways of aromatic polyketide biosynthesis.

The snoaL2 gene was ampliﬁed by PCR using Pfu DNA polymerase (Stratagene) and the pSYE67 plasmid10 as a template with the following oligonucleotides (restriction sites are underlined), 50-GTTCAGCTTCGTCATATGTCA ACGACCGCGAACAAG (forward primer) and 50-TGCC GCCGCAAGCTTCAGTCCGTCCGGCACCAC (reverse primer). The aclR gene was ampliﬁed by PCR from genomic DNA from S. galilaeus strain ATCC31133 with the oligonucleotides 50-CTGACGGCACATATGTCGATG GCTGAGCGCAA (forward primer), and 50-GACGGTAC GAAGCTTGGCGCTCGCTTCCAGGACCAC (reverse primer). Based on a sequence alignment between SnoaL2, SnoaL and AclR a different start codon was used for AclR than indicated in the data bank sequence (gi 16945726) leading to a 12 amino acid residue longer Crystal Structures of Polyketide Hydroxylases Crystal Structures of Polyketide Hydroxylases protein (Figure 2). This start codon is also preceded by a putative ribosome-binding site. The PCR products were digested with the restriction enzymes NdeI and HindIII and subsequently cloned into NdeI and HindIII restricted pET30b vector (Novagen). All cloned gene sequences were veriﬁed by DNA sequencing. The ampliﬁed AclR sequence showed one difference (Met65Val) compared to the data bank sequence from strain S. galilaeus 3AR-33.13 Expression of the constructs resulted in production of proteins with a seven amino acid C-terminal linker (Lys- Leu-Ala-Ala-Ala-Leu-Glu) followed by a hexa-histidine tag. In vivo expression of AclR

To construct a plasmid (pUHL) with a His6-tag linker inserted in pUC19, two oligomeric primers (50-CACTCT AGATCATGACACATCATCATCATCATCATAGCGCTC ACAGCTAGCAAGCTTCAC and its reverse comple- ment) were heated together in a boiling water bath and allowed to cool down slowly. The double-stranded DNA was digested with XbaI and HindIII and ligated into pUC19. The aclR gene was ampliﬁed by PCR with PhusionTM DNA polymerase (Finnzymes) using S. galilaeus ATCC 31133 genomic DNA as a template with the forward primer 5 0-CGAAGCGCTATGGCTGAGCGCAAGGCG CTG and the reverse primer 50-CAGAAGCTTTCAG GCGCTCGCTTCCATTAC. The ampliﬁed fragment was digested with Eco47III and HindIII and ligated with pUHL opened with the same enzymes. The ligation mix was electroporated into Escherichia coli strain TOP10 (Stratagene) and the sequence of the aclR gene was the aclR gene veriﬁed by DNA sequencing. Next, including the His-tag was cut out as a BspHI – HindIII fragment and ligated together with the ermE-rdmE promoter from plasmid pRDME*12)31 and the pIJ487 vector digested with EcoRI and HindIII. This ligation mix was directly transferred into S. lividans TK2432 protoplasts. The plasmid construct, pEHA, was isolated from S. lividans and subsequently introduced into S. galilaeus ATCC 31615 and the S. gali- laeus mutants H039 and H036.21

Transformants were cultured and the anthracycline products were recovered as described.33 For reference purposes, authentic 1-hydroxyaklavinone was produced with S. galilaeus DSM 40481 (ATCC 14969). HPLC analysis was performed as described,34 using a Phenomenex Luna 3u C18(2) 150 mm!2 mm column at a ﬂow rate of 0.2 ml/min. E. coli expression and puriﬁcation Protein production was carried using the E. coli strain BL21(DE3) as host. Cells were grown in LB medium at 37 8C. Expression was induced with IPTG (1 mM) at an A600 of 0.6 and the cultures incubated at 30 8C for 5 h. Cells were harvested (5000g for 20 min at 4 8C), resus- pended in 50 mM Tris–HCl (pH 7.5), 100 mM NaCl, centrifuged (5000g for 15 min at 4 8C), frozen in liquid N2 and stored at K20 8C. Seleno-methionine substituted SnoaL2 was produced by the methionine biosynthesis inhibition method.35 Cells were grown in M9 minimal medium supplemented with glucose (4 g/l), FeSO4 (0.5 mM), MgSO4 (1 mM), CaCl2 (0.1 mM), thiamine (0.001%, w/v) and vitamin B6 (0.0005%, w/v). Methionine biosynthesis was inhibited by the addition of inhibitory amino acids and seleno-

methionine (80 mg/l) was added to the cultures 15 min before induction. Induction was started by addition of 1 mM IPTG and incubation continued at 30 8C for 6 h. Cells were harvested (5000g for 20 min at 4 8C), resuspended in 50 mM Tris–HCl (pH 7.5), 100 mM NaCl, 10 mM DTT, centrifuged (5000g for 15 min at 4 8C) and stored at K20 8C. For lysis E. coli cells were resuspended in three to ﬁve volumes of lysis buffer (50 mM Tris–HCl (pH 7.5), 300 mM NaCl, 10 mM imidazole, 0.5 mg/ml lysozyme, 0.1 mM PMSF, 10 mg/ml DNase I). The disruption was completed by sonication (ﬁve pulses, 30 s each) and the debris was removed by centrifugation (40,000g for 30 min at 4 8C). The clear lysate was incubated for 1 h with Ni- NTA matrix (Qiagen, Hilden) at 4 8C. For protein puriﬁcation gravity ﬂow columns were developed. After extensive washing with wash buffer (50 mM Tris–HCl (pH 7.5), 300 mM NaCl, 30 mM imidazole) proteins were eluted with elution buffer (50 mM Tris–HCl (pH 7.5), 300 mM NaCl, 250 mM imidazole). The protein purity was analyzed by SDS-PAGE, the peak fractions pooled and dialyzed over night against 2 l protein storage buffer (20 mM Tris–HCl (pH 7.5), 25 mM NaCl). The protein solutions were ﬁltered (pore size 0.2 mM) and concen- trated to a ﬁnal concentration of 25 mg/ml using Centriprep centrifugation devices (Amicon). The typical yields of the puriﬁcations were approximately 40 mg of puriﬁed homogenous protein per liter of LB medium and 3 mg of

trated to a ﬁnal concentration of 25 mg/ml using Centriprep centrifugation devices (Amicon). The typical yields of the puriﬁcations were approximately 40 mg of puriﬁed homogenous protein per liter of LB medium and 3 mg of protein when M9 medium was used. Protein concentrations were determined using the Bradford method. For the puriﬁcation of seleno-methionine con- taining SnoaL2 5 mM b-mercaptoethanol was added to all buffers. Quantitiative incorporation of seleno-methionine in SnoaL2 was conﬁrmed by mass spectrometry.

The potential nogalonic acid methyl ester cyclase activities of SnoaL2 and AclR were measured as described.17 Assays for 1-hydroxylation were carried out at various conditions using puriﬁed recombinant SnoaL2 and AclR produced in E. coli, cell-free lysates from S. galilaeus H039/pEHA and by bioconversion31 using S. lividans TK24/pEHA. Dithranol, nogalonic acid, nogalonic acid methyl ester, auraviketone and aklavinone were used as potential substrates or substrate analogues. Crystallization and data collection Crystals of SnoaL2 were obtained by the hanging drop vapor diffusion method at 20 8C. Aliquots (1.5 ml) of a protein solution (24 mg/ml) containing 1 mM aklavinone were mixed with equal amounts of the reservoir solution consisting of 0.1 M Mes (pH 6.5), 18–20% (v/v) PEG 8000 and 0.2 M MgSO4 and equilibrated against 1 ml of well solution. Needle-shaped crystals appeared after three to four days and were suitable for X-ray structure analysis. Before data collection crystals were brieﬂy incubated in cryo-protectant solution (50% (v/v) mother liquor, 50% PEG 400) and frozen in liquid nitrogen. The crystals were transferred into a nitrogen stream at 110 K at the beamline ID14-3 at the ESRF (Grenoble, France). Crystals of seleno- methionine substituted SnoaL2 grew under identical conditions and were treated identical to crystals of the native protein. Diffraction data were collected at beamline ID23-1 at the ESRF (Grenoble, France) using a MarCCD detector. Crystals of cubic shape appeared after two days at 20 8C. Crystals were soaked in cryo-protectant solution (0.1 M Mes (pH 6.5), 20% PEG 400 and 20% glycerol) for 30 s and ﬂash-frozen by direct transfer into a gaseous nitrogen stream at 110 K. In the case of putative enzyme– ligand complexes of AclR and SnoaL2, obtained either by co-crystallization or soaking, the ligands in question were added to the cryo-solution to avoid depletion of the binding site. Diffraction data were collected at beamline ID 14-4 at the ESRF (Grenoble, France) using a Quantum 4R ADSC detector. Diffraction data were processed and scaled using the programs MOSFLM and SCALA from the CCP4 suite.36 Crystals of SnoaL2 belonged to the trigonal space group P3221 with unit cell dimensions of aZbZ90.5 A˚ , cZ 116.7 A˚ , and gZ1208. The asymmetric unit contained one dimer of SnoaL2, giving a solvent content of 68%. AclR crystallized in the orthorhombic space group P212121 with cell dimensions aZ80.9 A˚ , bZ81.7 A˚ , cZ136.6 A˚ and aZbZgZ908. The solvent content of the crystals is 60%, with two dimers of AclR in the asymmetric unit. The statistics for the data sets are given in Table 2.

The data set for native SnoaL2 showed hemihedral twinning (apparent space group P622) with a twinning fraction of 31.4% as determined using the Merohedral Crystal Twinning Server.37 Molecular replacement using different search models derived from the structure of SnoaL17 (26% sequence identity) was not successful and a MAD experiment with seleno-methionine substituted SnoaL2 was carried out. Crystals of seleno-methionine substituted protein were not twinned. The atomic positions of the selenium atoms were found using data collected at three wavelengths (Table 1) with the program SOLVE38 and the heavy-atom parameters were reﬁned with MLPHARE.36 The ﬁgure of merit at 3.0 A˚ resolution was 0.49 after heavy-atom reﬁnement, and increased to 0.76 after solvent ﬂattening and phase extension to 2.5 A˚ . The correct enantiomer for the space group was chosen by visual inspection of the electron density maps obtained after solvent ﬂattening. An initial polyalanine model was built using RESOLVE,39 and manual model building based on 2FoKFc and FoKFc electron density maps was carried out using the program WinCoot.40,41 The program Refmac5 was employed for restrained reﬁnement with TLS.42 The peak data set of seleno-methionine substituted SnoaL2 was used throughout the reﬁnement because these crystals were not twinned, and the resolution of the data is slightly higher than that from native crystals.
